      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm looking at some paperwork for a shipment from ningbo and i'm a bit confused. can u explain the main difference between CIF and FOB under incoterms 2020? specifically who handles the insurance and when does the risk actually transfer to us?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The main difference lies in who manages the shipping and insurance responsibilities. With CIF (Cost, Insurance, and Freight), the seller is responsible for arranging and paying for the insurance and the main carriage to the destination port. For FOB (Free On Board), the buyer takes over responsibility, including arranging and paying for insurance and the main freight, once the goods are loaded onto the vessel at the port of origin. The risk transfers to you under FOB as soon as the goods pass the ship's rail in Ningbo, whereas under CIF, the risk transfers to you once the goods are loaded onto the vessel at the origin, even though the seller paid for the insurance.",
      "source": "target",
